The <O wordnetid="106832680" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../758/18056758.xml">
Berkeley Timesharing System</link></O>
 was a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../958/30958.xml">
time-sharing</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../194/22194.xml">
operating system</link> for <company wordnetid="108058098" confidence="0.8">
<institution wordnetid="108053576" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../953/1302953.xml">
Scientific Data Systems</link></institution>
</company>
' <computer wordnetid="103082979" confidence="0.8">
<artifact wordnetid="100021939" confidence="0.8">
<instrumentality wordnetid="103575240" confidence="0.8">
<device wordnetid="103183080" confidence="0.8">
<machine wordnetid="103699975" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../534/3539534.xml">
SDS 940</link></machine>
</device>
</instrumentality>
</artifact>
</computer>
 computer and was designed and implemented between 1964 and 1967 at the <university wordnetid="108286163" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<ranking wordnetid="114429484" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../922/31922.xml">
University of California, Berkeley</link></ranking>
</university>
 as part of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../869/267869.xml">
Project Genie</link>. It was marketed as the first commercial time-sharing which allowed user programming in <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../683/20683.xml">
machine language</link>.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%221%22])">1</ref><p>

Except for the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../924/66924.xml">
memory management</link>, this system was copied directly in the design of the <O wordnetid="106832680" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../380/66380.xml">
TENEX</link></O>
 operating system for the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../628/23628.xml">
PDP-10</link> mainframe computer. Some concepts of the operating system also influenced the design of <family wordnetid="108078020" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../642/31642.xml">
Unix</link></family>
, whose designer <person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<scientist wordnetid="110560637" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../747/10817747.xml">
Ken Thompson</link></scientist>
</person>
 worked on the SDS 940 while at Berkeley. Students who worked on the Berkeley Timesharing System include <physical_entity wordnetid="100001930" confidence="0.8">
<peer wordnetid="109626238" confidence="0.8">
<person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.8">
